1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 12 MRSA §10902, sub-§8, as amended by PL 2013, c. 538, §§9 to 11, is
3 further amended by amending the first blocked paragraph to read:
4 The commissioner shall suspend a person's fishing license for 5 10 years and may suspend
5 any other license issued under this Part and held by that person if the person is convicted
6 or adjudicated of illegally importing, transporting or possessing live freshwater fish or fish
7 gametes of an offense under sections 12509, 12510, and 12512 and 12611, except that this
8 mandatory revocation does not apply to offenses under section 12509 involving live bait
9 fish or smelts.
10 Sec. 2. 12 MRSA §12509, sub-§1, as amended by PL 2019, c. 113, Pt. C, §20, is
11 further amended to read:
12 1. Permit required. Except as otherwise authorized pursuant to this Part, a person
13 may not introduce, import or transport any live fish or gametes fish eggs into the State or
14 receive or have in that person's possession fish or gametes fish eggs so introduced, imported
15 or transported without a valid permit issued under this section.
16 A person who violates this subsection commits a Class E crime, except that,
17 notwithstanding Title 17‑A, section 1704, the fine may not be less than $1,000 nor more
18 than $10,000.
19 Sec. 3. 12 MRSA §12509, sub-§2, as enacted by PL 2003, c. 414, Pt. A, §2 and
20 affected by c. 614, §9, is amended to read:
21 2. Issuance. The commissioner may grant permits to introduce, import or transport
22 any live fish or gametes fish eggs into the State or to receive or have in possession fish or
23 gametes fish eggs so introduced, imported or transported if the commissioner determines
24 that the species does not pose an unreasonable risk to any species of fish or other organism
25 after evaluating fish health, habitat and population management issues. The commissioner
26 may not adopt rules or issue permits governing any aspect of either the commercial
27 aquaculture of Atlantic salmon when intended for use in commercial aquaculture in coastal
28 waters or the Atlantic salmon restoration program.
29 Sec. 4. 12 MRSA §12509, sub-§3, ¶C, as enacted by PL 2003, c. 414, Pt. A, §2
30 and affected by c. 614, §9, is amended to read:
31 C. A statement from a fish health inspector certified by the American Fisheries
32 Society, a fish pathologist certified by the American Fisheries Society or a licensed
33 accredited veterinarian, certifying that the fish or gametes fish eggs are from sources
34 that show no evidence of viral hemorrhagic septicemia, infectious pancreatic necrosis,
35 infectious hematopoietic necrosis, Myxosomo cerebralis or other diseases that may
36 threaten fish stocks within the State; and
37 Sec. 5. 12 MRSA §12510, as amended by PL 2019, c. 113, Pt. C, §21 and c. 263,
38 §1, is further amended to read:
39 §12510. Permit to stock inland waters
40 1. Permit required. Except as otherwise authorized pursuant to this Part, a person
41 may not introduce fish or fish eggs of any kind into any inland waters without a valid permit
42 issued under this section. A person who violates this subsection commits a Class E crime,
Page 1 - 132LR0573(01)

413 except that, notwithstanding Title 17‑A, section 1704, the fine may not be less than $1,000
424 or more than $10,000.
3 1-A. Penalty. A person who violates subsection 1 commits a Class E crime, except
4 that, notwithstanding Title 17-A, section 1704, the fine may not be less than $1,000 or more
5 than $10,000.
6 1-B. Restitution. In the case of a person who violates subsection 1, the court shall:
7 A. Order that person to pay the department an amount equal to the cost of labor,
8 equipment, chemicals and all other related expenses directly associated with mitigating
9 or reclaiming waters affected as a result of the violation; and
10 B. Direct that person to provide the commissioner, upon making full payment as
11 ordered by the court under paragraph A, proof of that payment.
12 2. Issuance. The commissioner may issue a written permit allowing a person to
13 introduce fish or fish eggs of any kind into any inland waters by means of live fish or
14 otherwise.
15 3. Limited permit. The commissioner may issue a written limited permit to a local
16 government under this subsection. A limited permit:
17 A. Allows the local government to introduce fish or fish eggs only into a great pond
18 that:
19 (1) Is within the jurisdiction of the local government; and
20 (2) Was previously stocked by the department and in which stocking was
21 suspended prior to January 1, 2019 and has not been resumed by the department
22 due to inadequate public access;
23 B. Allows the introduction of only:
24 (1) The same species of fish that was stocked at the time the department suspended
25 stocking; and
26 (2) Fish or fish eggs obtained by the local government at its own expense from an
27 in-state commercial facility that meets testing and health guidelines approved by
28 the department; and
29 C. May be issued only if the local government identifies public access to the great
30 pond that:
31 (1) Is at least suitable for the hand carrying of boats to the water;
32 (2) Includes a parking area; and
33 (3) Has been marked with signage adequate to ensure public awareness of the
34 public access.
35 For purposes of this subsection, "local government" means a municipality or, in the
36 unorganized territory, a county.
37 Sec. 6. 12 MRSA §12511, as amended by PL 2019, c. 113, Pt. C, §22, is further
38 amended to read:
39 §12511. Permit to introduce fish or fish spawn eggs into private pond
