1 1. Permit required. Except as otherwise authorized pursuant to this Part, a person
2 may not introduce fish or fish spawn eggs into a private pond without a valid permit issued
3 under this section. A person who violates this subsection commits a Class E crime, except
4 that, notwithstanding Title 17‑A, section 1704, the fine may not be less than $1,000 nor
5 more than $10,000.
6 1-A. Penalty. A person who violates subsection 1 commits a Class E crime, except
7 that, notwithstanding Title 17-A, section 1704, the fine may not be less than $1,000 or more
8 than $10,000.
9 1-B. Restitution. In the case of a person who violates subsection 1, the court shall:
10 A. Order that person to pay the department an amount equal to the cost of labor,
11 equipment, chemicals and all other related expenses directly associated with mitigating
12 or reclaiming waters affected as a result of the violation; and
13 B. Direct that person to provide the commissioner, upon making full payment as
14 ordered by the court under paragraph A, proof of that payment.
15 2. Issuance. The commissioner may issue a written permit to introduce fish or fish
16 spawn eggs into a private pond.
17 Sec. 7. 12 MRSA §12512, as amended by PL 2019, c. 113, Pt. C, §23, is further
18 amended to read:
19 §12512. Permit to transport live fish for breeding and advertising
20 1. Permit required. Except as otherwise authorized pursuant to this Part, a person
21 may not take and transport within the limits of the State live fish taken in the State for
22 breeding or advertising purposes, other than baitfish and smelts, without a valid permit
23 issued under this section. A person who violates this subsection commits a Class E crime,
24 except that, notwithstanding Title 17‑A, section 1704, the fine may not be less than $1,000
25 nor more than $10,000.
26 2. Issuance. The commissioner may issue a permit to a person permitting that person
27 to take and transport within the limits of the State fish taken in the State for breeding or
28 advertising purposes.
29 Sec. 8. 12 MRSA §12557 is enacted to read:
30 §12557. Disposal of live baitfish or smelts
31 1. Prohibition. A person may not dispose of any live baitfish or smelts into inland
32 waters of the State.
33 2. Penalty. The following penalties apply to violations of this section.
34 A. A person who violates subsection 1 commits a civil violation for which a fine of
35 not less than $100 nor more than $500 may be adjudged.
36 B. A person who violates subsection 1 after having been adjudicated as having
37 committed 3 or more civil violations under this Part within the previous 5-year period
38 commits a Class E crime.
Page 3 - 132LR0573(01)

1 SUMMARY
22 This bill increases the suspension and revocation of a fishing license from 5 years to
33 10 years for the following 3 offenses: failing to acquire a permit to import live freshwater
44 fish or eggs except for live baitfish or smelts, to stock inland waters and to import live fish
55 taken within the State. It reduces the mandatory suspension of a fishing license for the
66 violation of illegal possession of live fish from 5 years to one year.
7 It adds mandatory restitution for failing to acquire a permit to stock inland waters and
8 failing to acquire a permit to introduce fish or fish eggs into a private pond, and the court
9 must order an offender to pay the Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife an amount
10 equal to the cost of labor, equipment, chemicals and all other related expenses directly
11 associated with mitigating or reclaiming waters affected as a result of a violation and direct
12 the offender to provide the Commissioner of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife proof of that
13 payment.
14 Current law requires a permit to transport live fish for breeding and advertising. The
15 bill eliminates the specific activities of breeding and advertising so the permit is required
16 more generally for transport of live fish except for live baitfish and smelts taken within the
17 State.
18 The bill creates a prohibition for disposal of live baitfish or smelts into inland waters,
19 which is a civil violation. It also changes references to gametes and fish spawn to fish eggs.
